text:
Creating on Tinkercad Make a Tinkercad account at https://accounts.autodesk.com/register On the website, you can click on the button that says “Join Now”. Click on the button that says “Create New Design”. Choose from any of the shapes on the right hand side of website. Move the shapes into the 3D build plate, click and drag them. Create a file folder. Go to the desktop and right click on the screen. A menu should pop up. Click on “New” Click on “folder.” Name the folder. Call it "3D Object." Export the Tinkercad file. Click on the button that says export file. Export the file as an “.STL”. Save the .STL to the created file. Click on the little arrow next to the download. Click the option “Show in Folder.” Move the .STL to the folder called “3D object.” Click and drag the file into the folder, it should appear among the other folders on the left hand panel of the screen. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Moving-Folders.png/459px-Moving-Folders.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Moving-Folders.png/760px-Moving-Folders.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Importing to Makerbot Print Open Makerbot Print on the computer. Double click on the program shortcut on the home screen, or by searching for it in the taskbar. If “Makerbot Print” isn't installed on the computer, follow the link to download it first at https://www.makerbot.com/3d-printers/makerbot-print/download/. Create a Makerbot Account or sign into an existing one. Import the .STL files into Makerbot. Click the “File” button in the left hand corner of the screen, then click on “Insert File.” {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/51/Insert-a-File.png/460px-Insert-a-File.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/51/Insert-a-File.png/760px-Insert-a-File.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Find the file folder named “3D object, that should be located on the desktop. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/35/Finding-your-Folder.png/459px-Finding-your-Folder.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/35/Finding-your-Folder.png/759px-Finding-your-Folder.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Double click on the file folder and select the .STL file. Click the button on the bottom of the file explorer that says “open.” {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Open-the-Folder.png/459px-Open-the-Folder.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Open-the-Folder.png/759px-Open-the-Folder.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Exporting from Makerbot Print # Connect the printer via the USB cable to the laptop or desktop computer. Select it as the printer on the computer. Export the file. Click on the red button in the bottom right hand corner of the screen that says export. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dd/Export-your-print.png/459px-Export-your-print.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dd/Export-your-print.png/759px-Export-your-print.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Find the folder named “3D object,” double click on that. Name the file. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Rename.png/459px-Rename.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Rename.png/759px-Rename.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Click “Save.” Check to see if the following message pops up on the screen. If so, the print has exported successfully. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/30/Success-message-from-Makerbot.png/460px-Success-message-from-Makerbot.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/30/Success-message-from-Makerbot.png/760px-Success-message-from-Makerbot.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Move the "3D Object" folder onto a USB Drive. Plug the USB into the computer. A message should pop up in the lower right-hand corner of the screen. This means that the USB has been installed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Installed-successfully.png/460px-Installed-successfully.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Installed-successfully.png/760px-Installed-successfully.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":325,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":537.6373626373627,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Double click on the folder labeled "3D Object'. Transfer the folder to the USB. Click and drag the name of the folder to the name of the USB drive, found on the left hand panel of the screen. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Moving-to-the-USB-Drive.png/460px-Moving-to-the-USB-Drive.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Moving-to-the-USB-Drive.png/760px-Moving-to-the-USB-Drive.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Eject the USB Drive. Click on the ^ button on the bottom right hand side of the screen. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f3/Right-Hand-Screen-Corner.png/460px-Right-Hand-Screen-Corner.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/f/f3/Right-Hand-Screen-Corner.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":278,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":459.73534971644614,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Go up to the picture that looks like a USB drive and right click on it. Click on the option that says “Eject DISK.” {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/56/Eject-DISK.png/460px-Eject-DISK.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/5/56/Eject-DISK.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":347,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":573.304347826087,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} The device is safe to remove when the following message appears in the bottom right hand corner of the screen. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/55/Safety-message-from-windows.png/460px-Safety-message-from-windows.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/5/55/Safety-message-from-windows.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":293,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":483.8800705467372,"licensing":"

License: Fair Use (screenshot)

"} Insert the USB port on the top right-hand side of the printer. Select the “Print” option. Select "Print" by pushing the big silver button/knob on the printer. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c4/Select-Print.png/460px-Select-Print.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c4/Select-Print.png/759px-Select-Print.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":220,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":363.2967032967033,"licensing":"

Image by: Uploader
License: Creative Commons

"} Choose the “USB Storage” option. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Select-the-storage.png/460px-Select-the-storage.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Select-the-storage.png/760px-Select-the-storage.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":226,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":372.6923076923077,"licensing":"

Image by: Uploader
License: Creative Commons

"} Choose the 3D Object folder. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e1/Selcting-your-Object.png/459px-Selcting-your-Object.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e1/Selcting-your-Object.png/759px-Selcting-your-Object.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":222,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":367.4725274725275,"licensing":"

Image by: Uploader
License: Creative Commons

"} Select the object and push the silver button. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Object-selection.png/460px-Object-selection.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Object-selection.png/759px-Object-selection.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":223,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":368.5164835164835,"licensing":"

Image by: Uploader
License: Creative Commons

"} Select the "Print" Option The object will be preparing to print when this screen comes up on the printer. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Success-screen-from-the-3d-Printer.png/460px-Success-screen-from-the-3d-Printer.png","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Success-screen-from-the-3d-Printer.png/760px-Success-screen-from-the-3d-Printer.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":219,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":361.2087912087912,"licensing":"

Image by: Uploader
